List comprehension is a single line syntax for creating a new list from existing iterables ( list, tuple, range).

Given three integers x, y, and z representing the dimensions of a cuboid, and an integer n, print a list of all possible coordinates [i, j, k] on a 3D grid such that:

0 ≤ i ≤ x
0 ≤ j ≤ y
0 ≤ k ≤ z
i + j + k ≠ n

Use list comprehensions rather than multiple loops.

> Solution:

if __name__ == '__main__':
    x = int(input())
    y = int(input())
    z = int(input())
    n = int(input())
    
    
    result = [[i,j,k]
            for i in range(1+x)
            for j in range(1+y)
            for k in range(1+z)
            if i+j+k != n]
            
    print(result)
